	In 1952, India had its first big vote where everyone, regardless of background, could vote. This was a major step in making sure everyone's voice was heard. As time went on, more and more people got involved in voting, and by 1967, different local groups started becoming more important in politics.

In 1989, they introduced Electronic Voting Machines (EVMs), making voting easier and faster. In 1996, there was no one big winner, so different parties had to work together to run the country. Then, in 2009, they added a new option on the ballot called "None of the Above" (NOTA), letting people say they didn't like any of the choices.

In 2014, a lot of people turned up to vote, showing that more folks were paying attention to what was happening in the country. The 2019 elections became the biggest in the world with over 900 million people having the chance to vote.

Even during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020-21, they found ways for people to vote safely. Now, in 2023, there are talks about changing some of the rules to make voting and elections even better. They're also discussing using technology more and making sure everyone knows why voting is important. So, elections in India are not just about choosing leaders but also about making sure everyone can be part of the decision-making.
